<DOC><DOCNO> AP890328-0135 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2044EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Czech-Rights     03-28 0167</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Czech-Rights,0174</SECOND><HEAD>Official Human Rights Committee Sends Letter To Premier</HEAD><DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An official human rights committeewrote a letter to the prime minister criticizing new legislation onhuman rights and proposing changes, the state news agency reportedTuesday.   In the letter, the government-appointed committee suggestedlegislators distinguish more clearly between civic rights andresponsibilities in March legislation that stiffens penalties forprotestors, the CTK agency said.   The official Human Rights Committee was established on Dec. 9 inan apparent move to offset rising protest.   So far, the committee has focused on helping citizens obtainexit permits and other cases of minor human rights abuse.   Some Czechoslovaks have accused the committee of failing tospeak against police brutality during a week of anti-governmentprotests in January that spurred the new legislation.   The protests focused on the anniversary of the Jan. 15, 1969,suicide of Jan Palach, who burned himself alive to protest theAugust 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed the ``Prague Spring''liberal reforms.</TEXT></DOC>